[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(20) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "In his days Edom revolted.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The connection of ideas is this: Although Jehovah was not willing to extirpate Judah, yet He suffered it to be seriously weakened by the defections recorded in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Kings 8:20-22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Made a king over themselves.—Josephus says they slew the vassal king appointed over them by Jehoshaphat (1Kings 22:48). Edom appears to have been subject to the hegemony of Judah from the time of the disruption under Rehoboam.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Made a king over themselves.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Josephus says they slew the vassal king appointed over them by Jehoshaphat (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Kings 22:48",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Edom appears to have been subject to the hegemony of Judah from the time of the disruption under Rehoboam.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Kings 8:20. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Kings 8:20",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "In his days Edom revolted — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "After they had been subject to Judah one hundred and fifty years, ever since the time of David, who subdued that country. This was a great dishonour to him. Hereby, however, the prophecy of Isaac (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 27:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") was fulfilled.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "8:16-24 A general idea is given of Jehoram's badness. His father, no doubt, had him taught the true knowledge of the Lord, but did ill to marry him to the daughter of Ahab; no good could come of union with an idolatrous family.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Edom, which had been reduced by David ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 8:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:15-16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but had apparently revolted from Solomon ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 11:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", was again subjected to Judah in the reign of Jehoshaphat ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 3:8-26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Edomites had, however, retained their native kings, and with them the spirit of independence. They now rose in revolt, and fulfilled the prophecy ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 27:40",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", remaining from henceforth a separate and independent people (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 25:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 27:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Amos 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). Kings of Edom, who seem to be independent monarchs, are often mentioned in the Assyrian inscriptions. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "18. daughter of Ahab—Athaliah, through whose influence Jehoram introduced the worship of Baal and many other evils into the kingdom of Judah (see 2Ch 21:2-20). This apostasy would have led to the total extinction of the royal family in that kingdom, had it not been for the divine promise to David (2Sa 7:16). A national chastisement, however, was inflicted on Judah by the revolt of Edom, which, being hitherto governed by a tributary ruler (2Ki 3:9; 1Ki 22:47), erected the standard of independence (2Ch 21:9).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
